5. Core Product Objective

The core objective of this wave is:

to let users begin recording more naturally from Telegram and Feishu by treating them as lightweight capture adapters that send input into the same Capture-first main chain, without creating independent bot-side business logic or new product centers.

This objective implies several important constraints:

1. adapter-first, not bot-product-first

TG bot and Feishu bot are entry surfaces, not product centers.

2. capture-first, structure-later

Bot input should create capture records first.
Parsing, pending, and formalization remain downstream.

3. same business logic center

The application service layer remains the only real business-logic center.
Bots do not become alternate logic systems.

4. lighter entry, not richer orchestration

The point is to make recording easier, not to turn messaging tools into workflow platforms.

6. What This Wave Is Not

This wave is not:

a Telegram product line
a Feishu product line
a bot management console
a review bot
an AI assistant bot
a workflow bot system
a multi-turn conversational agent
a direct-to-formal shortcut
a command/control center
a new platformization wave

It also does not imply:

Telegram management expansion
Feishu workflow platform expansion
Desktop role change
AI parsing/suggestion expansion
automation engine work
task orchestration work

These must remain explicitly outside the wave.

7. Product Meaning of TG Bot / Feishu Bot in TraceFold

Within this wave, TG bot and Feishu bot should each mean only one thing:

a lightweight message-to-capture adapter

That means:

the user sends text
the adapter submits it into Capture
the system acknowledges success/failure
downstream parse / pending / confirm still happen later
the user can continue in Web when deeper work is needed

The bot should be thought of as:

a very light recording doorway
not a place where the main work happens

This distinction is essential.

8. Recommended Wave Structure

I recommend structuring the wave around four work packages.

WP1 — Unified Adapter Contract
Purpose

Define one bounded contract for all message-based capture adapters.

Why first

Without a shared contract, TG and Feishu can easily grow into two independent logic branches.

What this work package should solve
unified input semantics
unified source metadata shape
unified success/failure response pattern
unified capture-first behavior
explicit boundary that adapters do not own downstream business logic
Important boundary

This is not a generalized adapter framework for everything.
It is a bounded contract for lightweight capture adapters.

WP2 — Telegram Quick Capture Bot V1
Purpose

Make Telegram a real lightweight quick-recording entry point.

Why Telegram first

Telegram already fits the project’s established “lightweight adapter” interpretation more naturally.
It is therefore the most natural first adapter to formalize.

First-version meaning
send text
create capture
get restrained feedback
keep the interaction light
no bot-side review actions
Important boundary

Telegram should remain an adapter, not become a control surface.

WP3 — Feishu Quick Capture Bot V1
Purpose

Bring Feishu into the same bounded adapter model.

Product meaning

Feishu should become:

a message-based lightweight entry path
not a workflow bot
not an approval/review platform
not a complex card/app system in the first wave
Important boundary

Feishu must not become a second, more enterprise-shaped business center.

WP4 — Adapter Usability Hardening
Purpose

Make the adapters actually feel “easy to start recording with.”

Areas of likely focus
clearer success feedback
better failure feedback
no silent input loss
cleaner capture-source traceability
clear handoff back into Web surfaces when deeper work is needed
bounded bilingual or user-facing copy alignment where useful
Important boundary

This is still usability hardening, not feature expansion into new bot roles.

9. Recommended Execution Order

I recommend the following order:

Wave 2-A

Unified Adapter Contract

Wave 2-B

Telegram Quick Capture Bot V1

Wave 2-C

Feishu Quick Capture Bot V1

Wave 2-D

Adapter Usability Hardening

This order keeps the wave stable:

define shared semantics first
formalize the more natural existing adapter first
then extend the same model to Feishu
then harden usability after both exist
10. Preserved Boundaries for This Wave

The following must remain true throughout this wave:

bots create capture records first
bots do not write formal records directly
bots do not bypass Pending or review semantics
bots do not execute confirm / discard / force_insert
bots do not own business logic
Web remains the main business interface
Desktop remains shell-level entry
Telegram and Feishu remain lightweight adapters
no AI parsing/suggestion expansion is introduced under the banner of “smarter bots”
no workflow / orchestration drift is introduced
11. Entry Criteria for the Wave

This wave is justified only because:

input friction reduction has already been established as the current Phase 3 theme
Wave 1 already strengthened Web-side intake
the next natural friction point is beginning capture from chat-like environments
the user explicitly wants recording to feel more like dropping a message in naturally

This is therefore a continuation of the same product problem, not a new unrelated direction.

12. Completion Definition for This Wave

A successful Lightweight Capture Adapters wave should make it true that:

Telegram and/or Feishu can act as lightweight message-to-capture entry surfaces
the adapters feel materially easier than opening deeper workbench surfaces for quick recording
all adapter inputs still remain capture-first
no adapter becomes a review or business-control surface
source traceability remains clear
the wave does not drift into bot platformization

This wave should not be judged by how “powerful” the bots look.
It should be judged by how naturally users can begin recording without breaking the architecture.

13. Drift Checks

This wave begins to drift if any of the following happen:

TG bot or Feishu bot starts growing bot-side workflow logic
adapters begin to execute formal review actions
adapters begin to bypass capture-first semantics
“helpful” behavior starts turning into AI parsing/classification expansion
the wave starts to resemble a management console or workflow system
Telegram or Feishu begins to act like a product center rather than an entry adapter

If this happens, the wave is no longer aligned.

14. Current Recommendation

The current recommendation is:

if TraceFold wants to keep improving low-friction daily recording after Phase 3 Wave 1, the cleanest next bounded direction is Lightweight Capture Adapters, starting from a unified adapter contract and a Telegram-first v1.

This recommendation assumes a continuing commitment to:

local-first
capture-first
service-centered semantics
restrained scope
adapter-not-center discipline
15. Next Step

The next appropriate planning step after this direction note is:

define the first executable work package: Unified Adapter Contract

That package should answer:

what the shared adapter contract is
what minimal metadata all adapters must provide
how success/failure should be handled
